ts; Joint inflammation, pain and disfigurement, chronic systemic inflammation. Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE): Autoantibodies directed against nuclear and cytoplasmic molecules form immune complexes that deposit in tissues. Phagocytic cells and complement activation cause tissue damage and inflammation; Fatigue, fever, joint pain and swelling, hair loss, anemia, clotting, a sunlight-sensitive “butterfly” rash, skin lesions, photosensitivity, decreased kidney function, memory loss, confusion, depression." class="span-all">
